04032nam a22004815i 9780804768061DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222006cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047680617 a10.1515/97808047680612doi  a(DE-B1597)582216  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aF2536b.N44 2006eb 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a981/.042221 aNeedell, Jeffrey D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Party of Order :bThe Conservatives, the State, and Slavery in the Brazilian Monarchy, 1831-1871 /cJeffrey D. Needell. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (480 p.) :b5 tables, 3 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Names, Titles, Spelling, and Translation -- tMaps: City of Rio de Janeiro, Province of Rio de Janeiro, Empire of Brazil -- tIntroduction: An Obscured Genesis -- tCHAPTER ONE The Port and Province of Rio de Janeiro -- tCHAPTER TWO The Threat of Revolution and the Reactionary Mobilization: 1831-1837 -- tCHAPTER THREE Political Theory, Partisan Practice, and the Emperor's Emergence: 1837-1848 -- tCHAPTER FOUR Provincial Politics, Foreign Affairs, and Patronage: 1848-1853 -- tCHAPTER FIVE The Transformation of Politics and the State: 1853-1867 -- tCHAPTER SIX Abolition, War, and the Vindication of Constitutional Government: 1867-1871 -- tCHAPTER SEVEN The Defeat of the Party: The Political Crisis of 1871 -- tConclusion: Legacy and Metamorphosis -- tGenealogical Tables -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis study analyzes Brazil's monarchy, which adapted European ideas and practices to a creole plantation society that was traditionally based on African slavery. It focuses upon the Conservatives, who represented the sugar and coffee elites in reconstructing the new nation's state as a strong, representative, constitutional monarchy in troubled times. After the monarch himself assumed power, however, his views undercut parliamentary and party government, which were also sapped by regional differences and the pressure for state patronage. Increasingly, the emperor and his cabinets used state patronage and state authority to dominate politics. When the emperor decided upon gradualist abolition, Conservatives were unable to defeat it, despite its unconstitutional origin and imposition and its threat to the society and economy they represented. The legacy of an authoritarian, centralized political culture survived; that of a representative, constitutional regime did not. This book dramatically revises notions of the monarchy in terms of the social and ideological origins and nature of the Brazilian state, the role of the monarch, and the range and complexity of elite politics in the era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aConservativeszBrazilxHistoryy19th century. 4aHistory -- Latin American. 4aHistory -- Political. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804768061zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804768061423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804768061/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles